    # [Scene: Roooftop Common Garden | Morning]

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle, rising piano with soft strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls; faint clink of watering cans]
    "You kneel between a row of reclaimed planters, fingers dark with compost. The leaves are damp with last night's fog; their edges glint like small promises. Around you the garden hums — bees that remember the"
    "herbal scents, a guttering solar lamp that still smells faintly of warm plastic, and the distant percussion of the harbor: cranes repeating a slow, mechanical respiration."
    "This morning arrives like the echo of a conversation you started months ago and kept having in different rooms. The campaign's momentum turned outward; you watched your notes become networks, your neighbor's testimony become policy leverage,"
    "your quiet spreadsheets become headlines. Now, the program you've argued for — city-funded, community-accountable retrofits — is moving from outline to ordinance."

    "You trace your wristband, feeling the small familiar weight of data and habit. There's a new title in the draft memo Samir sent last night, a line that surprised you and warmed a corner of your chest" "Mira Solace — Community Liaison, Harbor Resilience Program."
    "You hear footsteps on the gravel path. Arin appears through the low canopy, the morning light turning his hair to a halo of sand. He isn't in a suit; his jacket is patched in places and"
    "carries the smell of rope and coffee. He watches you for a beat, taking in the garden and the way you've got soil under your nails."
    show arin_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    arin_voss "You look like you built half this place with your hands and the other half with stubbornness."
    "You laugh — a short release. It loosens something."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "Stubbornness is a renewable resource here."
    "Arin steps closer, picking up a small trowel and examining the soil you just turned."

    arin_voss "They're actually doing it, Mira. Not just promises. The mayor's office signed the preliminary agreement last night. Samir's text blew up my phone at two in the morning."
    "You feel the information as a physical thing, the way data moves across your band, then settles into your chest. It's not relief yet — too many clauses still to be negotiated, too many neighborhoods to"
    "reach — but it is a tangible nudge toward something that could change how the city holds its people."

    mira_solace "We write the oversight body into the bylaws. Community seats, rotating audits, measurable thresholds for equity. No 'pilot' that stops at the wealth line."
    "Arin's smile is quick and crooked; it's earnest, but there's worry threaded through it."

    arin_voss "You always do the clauses that make the lawyers sigh and the elders clap. Which is the trade I like best."
    "You both pause, listening to the way the harbor sounds different in the morning — brighter, less like a threat, more like a place that will keep teaching you persistence."

    menu:
        "Tuck your notebook into your jacket and focus on logistics":
            "You slide your notebook into your jacket, the pages rustling around the list of community representatives. You speak numbers and timelines; Arin nods, sketching action into the margin of a plan in his head."
        "Stand and invite Arin to help plant a new row of salt-tolerant herbs":
            "You stand and hand him a small trowel. The work is quiet and immediate; your conversation softens to what will be done this afternoon, who will show up, and how the plants will hold when the wind comes."
        "Let the moment be private — ask Arin how he feels about all of it":
            "You drop the lists and ask him instead. His answer is messy and human: fierce optimism wrapped with fear for the people he grew up beside. He admits it aloud, and the confession makes the stakes feel less abstract."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues as written."
    "Arin folds his hands in the soil and laughs softly at your choice — the sound of someone choosing to stay."

    arin_voss "Okay. We do both. We plant, and we argue clauses later over tea."

    mira_solace "Tea and bylaws, then."
    "You smile, tasting the promise of both."
    hide arin_voss
    hide mira_solace

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Subtle swell — warmth threaded through optimism]
    # [Scene: Municipal Offices — Council Chamber | Midday]

    scene bg ch15_f99e88_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low brass and strings under a hopeful motif]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Murmurs of an assembled group; paper rustling; a distant bell indicating session start]
    "You enter the council chamber with Samir at your side and Etta moving like a compact center of gravity at the edge of the dais. The room smells of lemon oil and printed paper — the odd intimacy of bureaucracy that still feels like it can shelter something worth saving."
    show samir_hale at left:
        zoom 0.7

    samir_hale "They've allocated the initial fund, Mira. Ten million for retrofits, priority to low-income blocks and essential services. Etta's oversight proposal is in the packet."
    "You watch Samir's face during that sentence: relief lined with the habitual caution of someone who knows the language of contingency. His eyes find yours for a fraction of a second, and there's gratitude there that has always been practical rather than performative."
    show mira_solace at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mira_solace "We make the criteria public. We publish the audit schedule, the procurement rules, the performance indicators. Transparency isn't theater — it's scaffolding."
    "A councilmember at the front, a woman with salt-and-pepper hair and a voice like practiced tide, steps to the podium."

    "Councilmember Reyes" "We recognize the petitions, the hearings, and the work by dozens of collectives. Today's vote affirms the Harbor Retrofit Program, including community governance and measurable equity metrics."
    "Applause ripples, polite then steady. Etta's hands meet yours across the aisle; she squeezes with a firmness that carries decades. Her skin smells faintly of sea-salt and lavender, and the touch steadies you."
    show etta_maren at center:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_maren "You have the right hands on the wheel, child. Don't let the weight forget the breath."
    "You hold her gaze and translate her blessing into a vow you say only to yourself."

    "Mira Solace (internal)" "Promise to keep the program honest. Promise to write the clauses that cannot be laundered by good PR. Promise to carry the voices of the Old Pier, of Noah's boat shop, of the women who keep the markets lit when the forecasts say otherwise."
    "The mayor steps forward with a pen; a contract rests on the lectern. Cameras shutter in the back, but the ritual here is the real thing — signatures, words that bind, a network turning from rhetoric into tools."

    mira_solace "We will measure outcomes, not headlines."

    samir_hale "And we'll create a citizen audit panel. Rotating membership. No less than five community representatives, with real veto power on contract awards."

    "Councilmember Reyes" "Agreed. We will fund technical assistance for small businesses, and prioritize local labor contracts."
    "Etta's chin lifts. In her eyes you see a memory of a thousand small tests: the time a seawall was placed without asking, the time a grant vanished into a corporate ledger. This time, the memory seems to be addressed."
    "You breathe and make the small, deliberate choice that feels truer than polished lines."

    menu:
        "Read the prepared statement you rehearsed":
            "You step to the podium with your notes folded neatly. Your voice follows the script — precise, clear, designed to be quoted. The room nods along; the statement becomes a record."
        "Throw the notes away and speak from memory":
            "You fold the paper back into your notebook and speak instead from days spent in the Old Pier. Your words are ragged in places but honest; the room listens differently — leaning in, humanizing the promises into names and faces."

    # --- merge ---
    "The chamber receives the words and the narrative continues as written."

    mira_solace "We didn't get here by miracle. We got here because people showed up with their hands, their histories, and their evidence. This program belongs to them, and we will be judged by whether it keeps their lights on, their boats safe, and their stories connected to place."
    "The council chamber receives the words the way a harbor receives a tide — they are absorbed, shifting the contours. Cameras catch the moment; in Etta's face you see approval. Samir exhales like someone releasing a held breath."
    "When the mayor signs, then a dozen others do, the room exhales with them. It's a ceremonial inhalation, the kind that feels like a beginning."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A soft, synchronous clap when the last pen lifts]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: String flourish into a steady, warm chord]
    "Afterward, small conversations braid into each other — contractors negotiating community labor clauses, activists asking about inspection schedules, elders proposing cultural markers for retrofitted blocks. You move through them like water through reeds, listening, noting, refusing to let optimism outrun accountability."
    "Noah finds you near the rear exit, grease still under his nails, a jacket dusted with the harbor's memory."
    hide samir_hale
    show noah_solace at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_solace "So they finally made it real, huh? You did good."
    "You see the weight behind his compliment: the shop's lease, a family ledger, the creeping possibility of relocation if the retrofit plan overrides certain parcels. His words are cautious but warm."

    mira_solace "They're funding technical aid for small businesses and prioritizing local labor. We fought to make sure your shop isn't trimmed out of the plan."
    "Noah studies your face, measuring the certainty."

    noah_solace "I'll hold you to that, Mira. You know I will."

    mira_solace "Hold me. That's part of why I'm here."
    "He nods, then reaches out and bumps your shoulder with his palm — a brother's small benediction. The contact is ordinary and everything."
    hide mira_solace
    hide etta_maren
    hide noah_solace

